<br>
Because it makes use of govenment paid for roads, Rob.  That entitles the government to put stipulations on who is allowed to drive ON PUBLIC ROADS due to the danger you can so easily represent to others in a 2000 lb car going 100 mph.  Go live on a farm, drive there all you want - the government has no say in the matter there.<br>
<br>
&quot;1) No the corpse does not belong to the cemetary or the owner of the cemetary. Else the owner could dispose of the corpse anyway they want and there is some guy going to jail because of how he disposed of the corpses...&quot;<br>
<br>
Actually, I'd bet there is some level of legal stipulation on what is allowed to get a license to be a cemetary . . . though the social stigma of &quot;he takes stuff from teh corpses and sells the bodies to medical schools!&quot; would run a cemetary out of business in short order.  Though, come to think of it, you BUY a cemetary plot, right?  So the children/family actually own what is there . . . <br>
<br>
&quot;And as I asked earlier... why not all other drugs?<br>
Would you answer the same if instead of pot it was one of the other drugs?&quot;<br>
<br>
The disagreement we're having, Rob, is over the &quot;rightness&quot; and &quot;wrongness&quot; of a victimless crime - a situation where no one is harmed, but action taken was illegal.  You know, like oral sex in some states . . . <br>
<br>
Bottom line, I fail to see why anything that doesn't harm others in some way should be a crime.  /shrug<br>
<br>
